Note:
IEEE 754-2008 Decimal32 (decimal interchange format, 32 bits).

Reference: IEEE Std 754-2008, Section 3.5.2 (decimal interchange formats),
Section 5 (operations), Section 4 (rounding-direction attributes), and
Section 7 (default exception handling).

Format: 32 bits total
    sign       1 bit       (s)
    combination 11 bits    (G)         encodes biased exponent + leading digit
    coefficient 20 bits    (T)         encodes the remaining 6 BID-binary digits

Significand: 7 decimal digits (max value 9999999)
Biased exponent range: 0..191 (11-bit biased)
Exponent bias: 101
Unbiased exponent range: -101..+90 for normal (-95..+96 for "Quantum" exponent
                         per IEEE 754-2008 Table 3.6 with q = e - p + 1, p=7)

Encoding selected: BID (Binary Integer Decimal, Intel-style).
Rationale lives in the per-process @Reasoning blocks; in short, BID stores the
significand as a plain unsigned binary integer (0..9999999), which means
arithmetic can be performed with native 64-bit integer ops and only the
encode/decode boundary touches the bitfield layout. DPD would require packed
3-digit declets to be unpacked into binary before every multiply and re-packed
after, which is pure overhead on a CPU without dedicated decimal hardware.

Special values (IEEE 754-2008 Section 3.5.2):
    Infinity:    G[0..4]  = 11110, sign in s
    Quiet NaN:   G[0..5]  = 111110
    Signaling NaN: G[0..5] = 111111

Rounding modes implemented (IEEE 754-2008 Section 4.3):
    roundTiesToEven  (default for finance, the only IEEE-mandated default)
    roundTiesToAway  (round half up away from zero)
    roundTowardZero  (truncation)
    roundTowardPositive (ceiling)
    roundTowardNegative (floor)

Unpacked representation (in-memory triple used by all arithmetic):
    Allocated struct (32 bytes):
        offset 0  : sign        (0 = positive, 1 = negative)
        offset 8  : kind        (0 finite, 1 +Inf, 2 -Inf, 3 qNaN, 4 sNaN)
        offset 16 : coefficient (Integer; 0..9999999 for normalized finite)
        offset 24 : exponent    (Integer; unbiased decimal exponent)

The encoded 32-bit form lives in a single Integer (low 32 bits used).
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constants - IEEE 754-2008 Decimal32 parameters
Note: ============================================================================

Constant DEC32_PRECISION as Integer is 7
Constant DEC32_EMAX as Integer is 96
Constant DEC32_EMIN as Integer is -95
Constant DEC32_BIAS as Integer is 101
Constant DEC32_MAX_COEFF as Integer is 9999999
Constant DEC32_MAX_BIASED_EXP as Integer is 191

Constant DEC32_KIND_FINITE as Integer is 0
Constant DEC32_KIND_POS_INF as Integer is 1
Constant DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF as Integer is 2
Constant DEC32_KIND_QNAN as Integer is 3
Constant DEC32_KIND_SNAN as Integer is 4

Constant DEC32_ROUND_HALF_EVEN as Integer is 0
Constant DEC32_ROUND_HALF_UP as Integer is 1
Constant DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_ZERO as Integer is 2
Constant DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_POS as Integer is 3
Constant DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_NEG as Integer is 4

Constant DEC32_UNPACKED_SIZE as Integer is 32

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Power-of-ten table (10^0 .. 10^18 fit in 63-bit signed Integer)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_pow10" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Power-of-ten lookup. For Decimal32 the largest power we need during
    coefficient normalization is 10^7 (one digit beyond DEC32_PRECISION).
    During multiplication of two 7-digit coefficients we get up to 14 digits,
    which fits comfortably in a 63-bit Integer, so 10^14 is required for
    scale-down logic. We tabulate 10^0..10^18 because the same helper is
    reused by Decimal64 internally during cross-precision conversion and
    because 10^18 is the largest power that fits in a signed 63-bit Integer
    (10^19 = 10000000000000000000, which exceeds 2^63-1 = 9223372036854775807).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Reject n < 0 (return 0 as a sentinel; callers must not request a
       negative exponent here).
    2. Reject n > 18 (return 0 sentinel; out-of-range for 63-bit Integer).
    3. Iteratively multiply 1 by 10, n times. The loop is bounded by 18
       iterations so we do not need a lookup table allocation.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(n) but n is bounded above by 18. Inlining the loop avoids the cost
    of a table-allocation pass at module-init time, which matters for
    cold-start latency in batch financial reconciliation tools.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure function of n. No memory accesses, no allocation, no syscalls.
    Out-of-range n returns 0 which is a safe sentinel (decimal coefficient
    0 is meaningful but a divisor of 0 would surface as a separate divide
    error in callers).
    @End Security_Scope

    If n is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If n is greater than 18:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n:
        Set result to result multiplied by 10
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Integer absolute value helper (avoids dependency on a math module)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_abs" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Plain integer abs. We avoid Memory imports for a one-liner because every
    helper that runs inside the arithmetic loop must be inline-able by the
    backend; pulling in another module would add a call boundary that the
    backend cannot inline yet at this stage of the compiler.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branch on sign; negate via 0 minus value to avoid relying on a unary
    minus parse form that older bootstrap parsers may not accept on
    statement boundaries.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two compares and one subtract in the worst case. Used heavily in the
    rounding step and in dec32_count_digits.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure. Note: abs(MIN_INT) on a two's-complement machine is undefined in
    the abstract but at Decimal32 precision we never see anything close to
    2^62, so the pathological case cannot arise from valid Decimal32 data.
    @End Security_Scope

    If value is less than 0:
        Return 0 minus value
    End If
    Return value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Digit-count helper
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_count_digits" takes coeff as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Counts the number of decimal digits in a non-negative coefficient. This
    is used by the rounding/normalization step to decide how many positions
    must be shifted to bring the coefficient into the 7-digit precision
    window. We accept and tolerate up to 16-digit input because internal
    intermediates (e.g. coeff_a * coeff_b after a multiply) can grow that
    large before being scaled back. Decimal32 final results always have at
    most DEC32_PRECISION (7) digits.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walk a table of cumulative power-of-ten thresholds. For coeff < 10^k
    return k. Special case coeff == 0 returning 1 to match the conventional
    digit count of the literal "0".
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(log10 coeff). Iterative compare is faster than calling pow10 in a
    loop because the comparisons short-circuit at the first match.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure. Negative input is normalized to its absolute value before the
    decision so the result is always >= 1.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let v be dec32_abs(coeff)
    If v is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let count be 0
    While v is greater than 0:
        Set count to count plus 1
        Set v to v divided by 10
    End While
    Return count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Unpacked triple constructors and accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_unpacked_create" takes sign as Integer, kind as Integer, coefficient as Integer, exponent as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates a 32-byte struct holding the unpacked Decimal32 triple. The
    arithmetic primitives operate on this allocation form because it
    avoids re-decoding the BID layout on every step of a long
    accumulation, which is critical for column-oriented financial
    aggregations.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. allocate(32)
    2. Store sign at offset 0, kind at offset 8, coefficient at offset 16,
       exponent at offset 24.
    3. Return the pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single allocate call; struct lives on the owned-heap tier. For
    short-lived intermediates the caller should arena-allocate instead
    (a future optimization gated on the typed-arena pass).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Allocation failure returns 0 (a NULL sentinel). All callers in this
    module check for the 0 sentinel before dereferencing.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let p be Layout.allocate(DEC32_UNPACKED_SIZE)
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(p, 0, sign)
    __store(p, 8, kind)
    __store(p, 16, coefficient)
    __store(p, 24, exponent)
    Return p
End Process

Process called "dec32_get_sign" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return __load(p, 0)
End Process

Process called "dec32_get_kind" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return DEC32_KIND_QNAN
    End If
    Return __load(p, 8)
End Process

Process called "dec32_get_coefficient" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return __load(p, 16)
End Process

Process called "dec32_get_exponent" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return __load(p, 24)
End Process

Process called "dec32_destroy" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases the unpacked triple to the owned-heap allocator. Callers
    must call this once they have re-encoded the result back to the
    32-bit BID form, otherwise the per-operation allocation will leak.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Layout.deallocate is a no-op on 0, but we guard anyway for symmetry
    with the rest of the API.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). The deallocate path may quarantine the block under DEBUG
    canary builds but on release builds returns directly to the free
    list.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Double-free is detected by the underlying allocator and aborts the
    process via the canary protocol.
    @End Security_Scope

    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Layout.deallocate(p)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Special-value constructors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_make_zero" takes sign as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs a signed zero. IEEE 754-2008 distinguishes +0 and -0 in the
    sign-bit but they compare equal under all ordered comparisons. The
    exponent stored for zero is the "preferred" exponent 0 (q = 0) per
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.1 Note 2: zero results from arithmetic adopt
    the exponent dictated by the operation, but a "fresh" zero literal
    uses 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate via dec32_unpacked_create with kind = FINITE, coefficient = 0,
    exponent = 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path for accumulator initialization. Single allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    sign bits other than 0 or 1 are normalized to 1 (any non-zero treated
    as negative). This matches the bit-field semantics of the encoded
    form and prevents callers from injecting nonsense sign values that
    would break the sign-XOR in dec32_multiply.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let s be sign
    If s is not equal to 0:
        Set s to 1
    End If
    Return dec32_unpacked_create(s, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "dec32_make_infinity" takes sign as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs +Inf or -Inf. The coefficient and exponent fields are
    unused for infinities per IEEE 754-2008 Section 3.5.2 (the
    combination bits 11110 mark Inf and the remaining bits are
    "don't care" in interchange, but we store 0 for hygiene).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    sign is normalized to 0/1, then kind set to POS_INF or NEG_INF.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single allocation; used only in overflow handling and Inf/Inf inputs.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same sign-normalization rule as dec32_make_zero.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let s be sign
    If s is not equal to 0:
        Set s to 1
    End If
    Let kind be DEC32_KIND_POS_INF
    If s is equal to 1:
        Set kind to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF
    End If
    Return dec32_unpacked_create(s, kind, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "dec32_make_qnan" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Quiet NaN sentinel. IEEE 754-2008 Section 6.2 says qNaNs propagate
    silently through arithmetic; we do not need a payload at this stage
    of the bootstrap because no upstream stdlib consumes NaN diagnostic
    information.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate with kind = QNAN, sign = 0, coefficient = 0, exponent = 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single allocation; reached only on invalid-operation paths
    (0/0, Inf - Inf, sqrt of negative, etc.).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure. No external inputs.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return dec32_unpacked_create(0, DEC32_KIND_QNAN, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "dec32_make_snan" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Signaling NaN. Constructed only by user input (e.g. via the encoded
    bit pattern) per IEEE 754-2008 Section 6.2; arithmetic never produces
    sNaN. When an arithmetic op receives an sNaN it must signal invalid
    and propagate as qNaN; that conversion happens in dec32_propagate_nan.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate with kind = SNAN.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single allocation. Not on any hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure. The signaling semantics live in the operation handlers, not
    here.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return dec32_unpacked_create(0, DEC32_KIND_SNAN, 0, 0)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Predicates
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_is_zero" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If __load(p, 8) is not equal to DEC32_KIND_FINITE:
        Return 0
    End If
    If __load(p, 16) is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_is_finite" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If __load(p, 8) is equal to DEC32_KIND_FINITE:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_is_infinite" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let k be __load(p, 8)
    If k is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Return 1
    End If
    If k is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_is_nan" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let k be __load(p, 8)
    If k is equal to DEC32_KIND_QNAN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If k is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_is_signaling" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If __load(p, 8) is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_is_negative" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If __load(p, 0) is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NaN propagation helper
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_propagate_nan" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 6.2 specifies the NaN propagation order: if any
    operand is sNaN the result is qNaN and the invalid-operation flag is
    signaled; otherwise if any operand is qNaN the result is qNaN. We do
    not preserve payloads in v0.0.8.5 because no upstream consumer reads
    them yet, but the API leaves room for a payload-bearing version in a
    future revision.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Check sNaN first (a then b), then qNaN. Returns a fresh qNaN allocation
    so the caller can always destroy the returned pointer regardless of
    which operand triggered the propagation.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Called on every arithmetic op that might involve NaNs. Two pointer
    loads in the common (non-NaN) case where we return 0.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure given valid pointers. Returns 0 (no-NaN sentinel) if neither
    operand is NaN.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is not equal to 0:
        Let ka be __load(a, 8)
        If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
            Return dec32_make_qnan()
        End If
    End If
    If b is not equal to 0:
        Let kb be __load(b, 8)
        If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
            Return dec32_make_qnan()
        End If
    End If
    If a is not equal to 0:
        Let ka2 be __load(a, 8)
        If ka2 is equal to DEC32_KIND_QNAN:
            Return dec32_make_qnan()
        End If
    End If
    If b is not equal to 0:
        Let kb2 be __load(b, 8)
        If kb2 is equal to DEC32_KIND_QNAN:
            Return dec32_make_qnan()
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Round-to-precision (IEEE 754-2008 Section 4.3)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_round_coefficient" takes sign as Integer, coeff as Integer, exp as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Brings a coefficient and exponent pair into the 7-digit precision
    window. If the coefficient has more than DEC32_PRECISION digits we
    must shift right by the excess and apply the rounding rule from
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 4.3 to the discarded tail. The exponent is
    increased by the same shift to preserve mathematical value.

    We return a fresh unpacked triple. The function never returns 0 on
    success; it returns 0 only on allocation failure of the result.

    Underflow / overflow:
        After rounding, if the unbiased exponent exceeds DEC32_EMAX we
        return +/- infinity per IEEE 754-2008 Section 7.4 (overflow
        signal). If the exponent is below DEC32_EMIN we increase it by
        further shifting (subnormal handling); if even that cannot bring
        it into range we return signed zero (underflow to zero).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. If coeff == 0, return zero with exponent clamped to [EMIN, EMAX].
    2. Count digits; if <= PRECISION, no rounding needed; just check
       exponent range.
    3. Otherwise: compute excess = digit_count - PRECISION. Compute
       divisor = 10^excess. Split coeff into quotient = coeff / divisor
       and remainder = coeff - quotient * divisor.
    4. Determine round-up boolean per rounding_mode:
         HALF_EVEN: round up if remainder > divisor/2, or if remainder
                    == divisor/2 and quotient is odd.
         HALF_UP:   round up if 2*remainder >= divisor.
         TOWARD_ZERO: never round up.
         TOWARD_POS: round up iff sign == 0 and remainder > 0.
         TOWARD_NEG: round up iff sign == 1 and remainder > 0.
    5. Increment quotient if round_up; if that causes a digit-carry
       (quotient == 10^PRECISION) divide by 10 and bump exponent.
    6. Final exponent check: clamp / signal overflow / underflow.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Inside the rounding loop we use pow10 lookups bounded to <= 18
    iterations. No allocations until the final create.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure aside from the final allocation. coeff is treated as unsigned
    semantic (caller passes its absolute value plus a separate sign).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let c be coeff
    Let e be exp
    Let s be sign
    If s is not equal to 0:
        Set s to 1
    End If

    If c is equal to 0:
        Let ez be e
        If ez is greater than DEC32_EMAX:
            Set ez to DEC32_EMAX
        End If
        If ez is less than DEC32_EMIN:
            Set ez to DEC32_EMIN
        End If
        Return dec32_unpacked_create(s, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, 0, ez)
    End If

    Let digits be dec32_count_digits(c)
    If digits is greater than DEC32_PRECISION:
        Let excess be digits minus DEC32_PRECISION
        Let divisor be dec32_pow10(excess)
        If divisor is equal to 0:
            Return dec32_make_infinity(s)
        End If
        Let quotient be c divided by divisor
        Let remainder be c minus (quotient multiplied by divisor)
        Let round_up be 0
        Let half be divisor divided by 2

        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_HALF_EVEN:
            If remainder is greater than half:
                Set round_up to 1
            Otherwise:
                If remainder is equal to half:
                    Let last_digit be quotient minus ((quotient divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
                    If last_digit is not equal to ((last_digit divided by 2) multiplied by 2):
                        Set round_up to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_HALF_UP:
            If remainder is greater than or equal to half:
                If remainder is not equal to 0:
                    Set round_up to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_ZERO:
            Set round_up to 0
        End If
        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_POS:
            If s is equal to 0:
                If remainder is greater than 0:
                    Set round_up to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_NEG:
            If s is equal to 1:
                If remainder is greater than 0:
                    Set round_up to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If round_up is equal to 1:
            Set quotient to quotient plus 1
        End If
        Set e to e plus excess

        Let cap be dec32_pow10(DEC32_PRECISION)
        If quotient is greater than or equal to cap:
            Set quotient to quotient divided by 10
            Set e to e plus 1
        End If
        Set c to quotient
    End If

    Note: Overflow check: the value's MSD position is at decade
    Note: (e + digits(c) - 1). Per IEEE 754-2008 Section 7.4 the result
    Note: overflows when the value > 10^(EMAX+1) which is equivalent to
    Note: (e + digits(c) - 1) > EMAX.
    Let c_digits be dec32_count_digits(c)
    Let msd_decade be e plus c_digits minus 1
    If msd_decade is greater than DEC32_EMAX:
        Return dec32_make_infinity(s)
    End If

    If e is less than DEC32_EMIN:
        Note: Subnormal: shift coefficient right (with rounding) by the
        Note: deficit until exponent is in range. If coefficient hits 0
        Note: we have underflowed to zero.
        While e is less than DEC32_EMIN:
            If c is equal to 0:
                Return dec32_unpacked_create(s, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, 0, DEC32_EMIN)
            End If
            Let last be c minus ((c divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
            Let qsub be c divided by 10
            Let rup2 be 0

            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_HALF_EVEN:
                If last is greater than 5:
                    Set rup2 to 1
                Otherwise:
                    If last is equal to 5:
                        Let last_digit2 be qsub minus ((qsub divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
                        If last_digit2 is not equal to ((last_digit2 divided by 2) multiplied by 2):
                            Set rup2 to 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_HALF_UP:
                If last is greater than or equal to 5:
                    Set rup2 to 1
                End If
            End If
            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_POS:
                If s is equal to 0:
                    If last is greater than 0:
                        Set rup2 to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_NEG:
                If s is equal to 1:
                    If last is greater than 0:
                        Set rup2 to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            If rup2 is equal to 1:
                Set qsub to qsub plus 1
            End If
            Set c to qsub
            Set e to e plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return dec32_unpacked_create(s, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, c, e)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comparisons (operate on unpacked triples)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Three-way compare: returns -1 if a < b, 0 if equal, 1 if a > b. NaN
    cases are signaled by returning -2 so callers can distinguish unordered
    from "less than". This matches the IEEE 754-2008 compareQuietLess /
    compareSignalingEqual contract once the caller does the NaN-to-flag
    translation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Handle NaN unordered.
    2. Handle infinities by sign.
    3. For finite numbers, equal magnitudes if both zero return 0.
    4. Compare signs.
    5. For same sign, compare magnitudes by aligning exponents.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    The hot path (same-sign, similar-magnitude) requires a single
    align-and-compare loop that runs at most DEC32_PRECISION + 1 = 8
    iterations.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure. No allocation. NULL operand returns -2 (unordered).
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 2
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 2
    End If
    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let kb be __load(b, 8)
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_QNAN:
        Return 0 minus 2
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
        Return 0 minus 2
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_QNAN:
        Return 0 minus 2
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
        Return 0 minus 2
    End If

    Note: Infinity handling
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return 1
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let sb be __load(b, 0)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let cb be __load(b, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let eb be __load(b, 24)

    Note: Both zero are equal regardless of sign
    If ca is equal to 0:
        If cb is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    If sa is not equal to sb:
        If sa is equal to 1:
            Return 0 minus 1
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Same sign: compare magnitudes after exponent alignment.
    Note: Bring both to the same exponent (the smaller one) by scaling up
    Note: the coefficient of the side with the larger exponent.
    Let mag_a be ca
    Let mag_b be cb
    Let exp_diff be ea minus eb
    If exp_diff is greater than 0:
        Note: Scale up a's coefficient. Cap the scaling to prevent overflow.
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than exp_diff:
            If mag_a is greater than 922337203685477580:
                Note: ca's magnitude eclipses cb regardless of scaling
                If sa is equal to 1:
                    Return 0 minus 1
                End If
                Return 1
            End If
            Set mag_a to mag_a multiplied by 10
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    If exp_diff is less than 0:
        Let j be 0
        Let nd be 0 minus exp_diff
        While j is less than nd:
            If mag_b is greater than 922337203685477580:
                If sa is equal to 1:
                    Return 1
                End If
                Return 0 minus 1
            End If
            Set mag_b to mag_b multiplied by 10
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
    End If

    If mag_a is equal to mag_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    If mag_a is less than mag_b:
        If sa is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If sa is equal to 1:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "dec32_eq" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754-2008 compareQuietEqual. NaNs are unordered (never equal),
    so they return 0.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Wrap dec32_compare; treat -2 (unordered) as 0 (not equal).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One compare call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let c be dec32_compare(a, b)
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_ne" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754-2008 compareQuietNotEqual. NaNs are never equal so NaN
    comparisons return 1 (not equal).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Negate dec32_eq, but with NaN-handling: unordered (compare == -2) is
    "not equal" = 1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One compare call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let c be dec32_compare(a, b)
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "dec32_lt" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let c be dec32_compare(a, b)
    If c is equal to 0 minus 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_le" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let c be dec32_compare(a, b)
    If c is equal to 0 minus 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_gt" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let c be dec32_compare(a, b)
    If c is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "dec32_ge" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let c be dec32_compare(a, b)
    If c is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Negation and absolute value
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_neg" takes a as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754-2008 negate: flip sign bit; do not modify coefficient,
    exponent, or NaN payload. negate is a bit-level operation, not an
    arithmetic operation, so no rounding occurs (the parameter is
    retained for API symmetry with the other ops).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocate a fresh triple with sign flipped (0 <-> 1) and all other
    fields copied verbatim.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single allocation; no arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure. NaN propagates by copy (sign-flip on NaN is well-defined per
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 6.3).
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let new_sign be 1
    If sa is equal to 1:
        Set new_sign to 0
    End If
    Let new_kind be ka
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Set new_kind to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set new_kind to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF
    End If
    Return dec32_unpacked_create(new_sign, new_kind, ca, ea)
End Process

Process called "dec32_abs_value" takes a as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754-2008 abs: clear sign bit; no rounding.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Copy fields, set sign = 0, flip NEG_INF to POS_INF.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let new_kind be ka
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set new_kind to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF
    End If
    Return dec32_unpacked_create(0, new_kind, ca, ea)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Addition / subtraction (IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.1)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decimal addition with exact intermediate precision then a single
    correctly-rounded result. Both operands are aligned to a common
    exponent (the smaller of the two) by scaling the larger-exponent
    coefficient up by 10^diff. The sum then has at most max(digits_a,
    digits_b) + 1 = 8 digits, which fits in a 63-bit integer with
    enormous headroom. We then call dec32_round_coefficient to reduce
    back to the 7-digit precision per the rounding_mode.

    CORRECTNESS GUARANTEE: For inputs that are exact decimal values
    representable in Decimal32, the sum is computed in the integer
    domain with no intermediate loss of precision. This is the entire
    point of decimal floating-point: 0.1 + 0.2 in Decimal32 is
    coefficient 1 exp -1 + coefficient 2 exp -1 = coefficient 3 exp -1
    = 0.3 EXACTLY. The IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.1 "correctly rounded"
    requirement is therefore satisfied trivially for sums whose result
    digit count is <= 7; for sums that produce 8 digits we round in
    accordance with rounding_mode.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NaN propagation via dec32_propagate_nan.
    2. Infinity handling: +Inf + +Inf = +Inf, -Inf + -Inf = -Inf,
       +Inf + -Inf = qNaN (invalid). Finite + Inf = Inf (signed).
    3. Align exponents by scaling the higher-exponent coefficient up.
       If the scale factor exceeds 10^14 the smaller operand is below
       the precision threshold and we can treat it as zero (this is
       the "guard digit" optimization; we still round one extra digit
       to preserve correct rounding).
    4. Combine coefficients with sign-aware addition. If signs differ,
       subtract magnitudes and take the sign of the larger operand.
    5. Round result via dec32_round_coefficient.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path. The alignment loop is bounded by ~14 iterations (the
    maximum difference in exponents before one operand is negligible
    at Decimal32 precision). The actual addition is a single 64-bit
    add. The rounding step traverses at most one excess digit on
    cancellation-free sums and at most ~8 digits on subtractive
    cancellation (where leading digits cancel).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    NaN-propagation matches IEEE 754-2008 Section 6.2. Invalid
    operations (Inf + -Inf) produce qNaN.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let np be dec32_propagate_nan(a, b)
    If np is not equal to 0:
        Return np
    End If
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let kb be __load(b, 8)

    Note: Infinity handling
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
            Return dec32_make_qnan()
        End If
        Return dec32_make_infinity(0)
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
            Return dec32_make_qnan()
        End If
        Return dec32_make_infinity(1)
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Return dec32_make_infinity(0)
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Return dec32_make_infinity(1)
    End If

    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let sb be __load(b, 0)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let cb be __load(b, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let eb be __load(b, 24)

    Note: Align both operands at a single exponent so the coefficients
    Note: can be summed/differenced as integers. The natural choice is
    Note: exp_common = min(ea, eb) (scale both UP), but a Decimal32
    Note: coefficient has up to 7 digits and a 64-bit Integer holds
    Note: ~18.9 decimal digits, so the larger operand can be scaled up
    Note: by at most cap_shift = 11 digits without overflowing the
    Note: sum domain. When the exponent gap exceeds cap_shift, we
    Note: re-anchor exp_common UP to (max(ea,eb) - cap_shift) so the
    Note: larger operand scales by exactly cap_shift digits and the
    Note: smaller operand scales DOWN, with any discarded digits
    Note: captured as a sticky bit that biases the final rounding.
    Let cap_shift be 11
    Let max_exp be ea
    If eb is greater than ea:
        Set max_exp to eb
    End If
    Let min_exp be eb
    If ea is less than eb:
        Set min_exp to ea
    End If
    Let exp_common be min_exp
    If (max_exp minus min_exp) is greater than cap_shift:
        Set exp_common to max_exp minus cap_shift
    End If

    Let shift_a be ea minus exp_common
    Let shift_b be eb minus exp_common

    Let scaled_a be ca
    Let sticky_a be 0
    If shift_a is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than shift_a:
            Set scaled_a to scaled_a multiplied by 10
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Note: shift_a < 0 means we drop |shift_a| trailing decimal digits.
        Note: 19 covers the full Integer range, so any larger drop yields 0.
        Let down_a be 0 minus shift_a
        If down_a is greater than 19:
            If scaled_a is not equal to 0:
                Set sticky_a to 1
            End If
            Set scaled_a to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let k be 0
            While k is less than down_a:
                Let rem_d be scaled_a minus ((scaled_a divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
                If rem_d is not equal to 0:
                    Set sticky_a to 1
                End If
                Set scaled_a to scaled_a divided by 10
                Set k to k plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Let scaled_b be cb
    Let sticky_b be 0
    If shift_b is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than shift_b:
            Set scaled_b to scaled_b multiplied by 10
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Let down_b be 0 minus shift_b
        If down_b is greater than 19:
            If scaled_b is not equal to 0:
                Set sticky_b to 1
            End If
            Set scaled_b to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let kb be 0
            While kb is less than down_b:
                Let rem_db be scaled_b minus ((scaled_b divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
                If rem_db is not equal to 0:
                    Set sticky_b to 1
                End If
                Set scaled_b to scaled_b divided by 10
                Set kb to kb plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Combine with signs.
    Let result_sign be 0
    Let result_coeff be 0
    Let combined_sticky be sticky_a bitwise or sticky_b
    If sa is equal to sb:
        Set result_coeff to scaled_a plus scaled_b
        Set result_sign to sa
    Otherwise:
        If scaled_a is greater than scaled_b:
            Set result_coeff to scaled_a minus scaled_b
            Set result_sign to sa
            Note: Sign mismatch with positive A-B subtracts a slightly
            Note: larger B (the sticky digits we dropped from B). The
            Note: rounded difference is therefore <= the integer
            Note: difference; if any sticky is set we decrement by one
            Note: ULP-of-difference and re-flag sticky so the rounder
            Note: still sees that the true value lies between
            Note: result_coeff-1 and result_coeff.
            If sticky_b is not equal to 0:
                If result_coeff is greater than 0:
                    Set result_coeff to result_coeff minus 1
                    Set combined_sticky to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If scaled_b is greater than scaled_a:
            Set result_coeff to scaled_b minus scaled_a
            Set result_sign to sb
            If sticky_a is not equal to 0:
                If result_coeff is greater than 0:
                    Set result_coeff to result_coeff minus 1
                    Set combined_sticky to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If scaled_a is equal to scaled_b:
            Set result_coeff to 0
            Note: Sign of zero from subtractive cancellation under
            Note: roundTiesToEven is +0; under roundTowardNegative it
            Note: is -0 per IEEE 754-2008 Section 6.3.
            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_NEG:
                Set result_sign to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set result_sign to 0
            End If
            Note: If only one operand contributed sticky, the true
            Note: difference is non-zero (smaller-magnitude operand
            Note: leaks below LSB). Adopt that operand's sign.
            If sticky_a is not equal to 0:
                If sticky_b is equal to 0:
                    Set result_sign to sa
                End If
            End If
            If sticky_b is not equal to 0:
                If sticky_a is equal to 0:
                    Set result_sign to sb
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: When sticky is non-zero we inject one extra LSB digit so the
    Note: rounder's HALF_EVEN / HALF_UP / directed-rounding decision
    Note: factors in the non-zero residual. To preserve the represented
    Note: value, we first pad result_coeff up to PRECISION significant
    Note: digits (decreasing exp_common to compensate), then multiply
    Note: by 10 and OR in the sticky bit. After this transform the
    Note: coefficient has PRECISION+1 digits, which always triggers the
    Note: rounder's excess-digit path. With a remainder of "1" the
    Note: rounder leaves the coefficient untouched for round-half cases
    Note: where the result is not exactly on a half boundary, and
    Note: breaks ties using the IEEE 754-2008 Section 4.3 rules.
    If combined_sticky is not equal to 0:
        Let cur_digits be dec32_count_digits(result_coeff)
        If cur_digits is less than DEC32_PRECISION:
            Let pad be DEC32_PRECISION minus cur_digits
            Let p_iter be 0
            While p_iter is less than pad:
                Set result_coeff to result_coeff multiplied by 10
                Set exp_common to exp_common minus 1
                Set p_iter to p_iter plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set result_coeff to (result_coeff multiplied by 10) plus 1
        Set exp_common to exp_common minus 1
    End If

    Return dec32_round_coefficient(result_sign, result_coeff, exp_common, rounding_mode)
End Process

Process called "dec32_sub" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.1 subtraction defined as a + (-b). We
    materialize a negated copy of b and delegate to dec32_add. The
    negation is bit-level so it preserves NaN payloads.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Build neg_b via dec32_neg(b, rounding_mode).
    2. Call dec32_add(a, neg_b, rounding_mode).
    3. Free neg_b before returning the sum.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One extra allocation versus a direct subtract. The alternative
    (inline subtractive path) would duplicate ~80 LOC of alignment
    logic; benchmarking on real workloads shows the allocation is
    negligible compared to the alignment loop.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same NaN/Inf handling as dec32_add.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let neg_b be dec32_neg(b, rounding_mode)
    If neg_b is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    Let result be dec32_add(a, neg_b, rounding_mode)
    dec32_destroy(neg_b)
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Multiplication (IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.1)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_mul" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decimal multiply: coefficient_a * coefficient_b at exponent
    exponent_a + exponent_b, with sign sign_a XOR sign_b. Both
    coefficients are at most 7 digits so the product is at most 14
    digits, which fits in 63-bit Integer with no overflow risk. The
    rounding step then reduces back to 7 digits.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NaN propagation.
    2. Inf cases: Inf * 0 = qNaN (invalid). Otherwise Inf * finite = Inf
       with combined sign.
    3. Zero cases: 0 * Inf = qNaN; 0 * anything else = signed 0.
    4. Compute coefficient product, exponent sum, sign XOR.
    5. Round to precision.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single 64-bit integer multiply plus a rounding step. Far cheaper
    than the binary-float multiply on most CPUs.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Inf * 0 generates qNaN with invalid-operation semantics per
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 7.2.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let np be dec32_propagate_nan(a, b)
    If np is not equal to 0:
        Return np
    End If
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let kb be __load(b, 8)
    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let sb be __load(b, 0)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let cb be __load(b, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let eb be __load(b, 24)

    Let result_sign be 0
    If sa is not equal to sb:
        Set result_sign to 1
    End If

    Let a_inf be 0
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Set a_inf to 1
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set a_inf to 1
    End If
    Let b_inf be 0
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Set b_inf to 1
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set b_inf to 1
    End If

    If a_inf is equal to 1:
        If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_FINITE:
            If cb is equal to 0:
                Return dec32_make_qnan()
            End If
            Return dec32_make_infinity(result_sign)
        End If
        Return dec32_make_infinity(result_sign)
    End If
    If b_inf is equal to 1:
        If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_FINITE:
            If ca is equal to 0:
                Return dec32_make_qnan()
            End If
            Return dec32_make_infinity(result_sign)
        End If
        Return dec32_make_infinity(result_sign)
    End If

    If ca is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_unpacked_create(result_sign, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, 0, ea plus eb)
    End If
    If cb is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_unpacked_create(result_sign, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, 0, ea plus eb)
    End If

    Let product be ca multiplied by cb
    Let exp_sum be ea plus eb
    Return dec32_round_coefficient(result_sign, product, exp_sum, rounding_mode)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Division (IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.1)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_div" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decimal division with correctly-rounded result. We pre-scale the
    dividend coefficient by 10^(PRECISION+1) to obtain a quotient with
    PRECISION+1 digits, then round to PRECISION via dec32_round_coefficient.
    The +1 guard digit ensures the rounding decision is made on the
    correct half-way information per IEEE 754-2008 Section 4.3.

    Special cases per IEEE 754-2008 Sections 6.1, 6.2, 7.2, 7.3:
        x / 0 with x != 0: signed infinity, signal divideByZero.
        0 / 0:             qNaN, signal invalid.
        Inf / Inf:         qNaN, signal invalid.
        finite / Inf:      signed zero.
        Inf / finite:      signed infinity.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NaN propagation.
    2. Sign of result: sign_a XOR sign_b (always; even for special values).
    3. Inf and zero handling per spec.
    4. Scale ca by 10^(DEC32_PRECISION+1) = 10^8 then divide by cb.
    5. Track the remainder for round-bit information; we feed the
       (quotient * 10 + something_to_indicate_remainder) into the
       rounding step. To keep things tractable we instead include the
       guard digit by scaling, and the round step uses the next-lower
       digit naturally.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single 64-bit divide. The scaling is a single multiply by 10^8 =
    100000000 which is well within 63-bit Integer range for the
    7-digit dividend (max 9999999 * 10^8 = ~10^15 which is below 2^63).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Division by zero with non-zero dividend signals divideByZero per
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 7.3. We return signed infinity per the
    default exception handling.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let np be dec32_propagate_nan(a, b)
    If np is not equal to 0:
        Return np
    End If
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let kb be __load(b, 8)
    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let sb be __load(b, 0)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let cb be __load(b, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let eb be __load(b, 24)

    Let result_sign be 0
    If sa is not equal to sb:
        Set result_sign to 1
    End If

    Let a_inf be 0
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Set a_inf to 1
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set a_inf to 1
    End If
    Let b_inf be 0
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Set b_inf to 1
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set b_inf to 1
    End If

    If a_inf is equal to 1:
        If b_inf is equal to 1:
            Return dec32_make_qnan()
        End If
        Return dec32_make_infinity(result_sign)
    End If
    If b_inf is equal to 1:
        Return dec32_unpacked_create(result_sign, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, 0, 0)
    End If

    Note: Both finite.
    If cb is equal to 0:
        If ca is equal to 0:
            Return dec32_make_qnan()
        End If
        Return dec32_make_infinity(result_sign)
    End If
    If ca is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_unpacked_create(result_sign, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, 0, ea minus eb)
    End If

    Note: Scale dividend by 10^(PRECISION+1) for the guard digit.
    Let scale be dec32_pow10(DEC32_PRECISION plus 1)
    Let scaled_ca be ca multiplied by scale
    Let quotient be scaled_ca divided by cb
    Let remainder be scaled_ca minus (quotient multiplied by cb)
    Note: If remainder is non-zero, we OR a sticky bit into the last
    Note: position of the quotient so that half-way ties are broken
    Note: correctly. We implement this by ensuring the last digit is
    Note: odd whenever the true result is not exactly representable.
    If remainder is not equal to 0:
        Let lastq be quotient minus ((quotient divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
        If lastq is equal to 0:
            Set quotient to quotient plus 1
        End If
    End If
    Let new_exp be ea minus eb minus DEC32_PRECISION minus 1
    Return dec32_round_coefficient(result_sign, quotient, new_exp, rounding_mode)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Fused multiply-add (IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.1)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_fma" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, c as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes (a * b) + c with a single correctly-rounded result, per
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.1. The intermediate product is exact in
    the integer domain (14 digits worst case for Decimal32), so the
    fused form differs from naive (a*b) + c only by skipping the
    intermediate rounding. The single rounding at the end is what
    makes FMA preferred for polynomial evaluation and dot-product
    accumulation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NaN propagation across all three operands (handle a/b/c).
    2. Inf handling: a*b = Inf with c != opposite-Inf -> Inf; a*b = Inf
       with c = opposite-Inf -> qNaN.
    3. Compute the unrounded product as (sign_p, coeff_p, exp_p) where
       coeff_p = ca * cb (exact), exp_p = ea + eb, sign_p = sa XOR sb.
    4. Align the product with c at the smaller exponent.
    5. Add or subtract magnitudes per sign rules.
    6. Round once via dec32_round_coefficient.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single integer multiply + add + round. Skips the intermediate
    rounding that naive (a*b) + c would do, which is exactly the
    accuracy advantage IEEE 754-2008 codifies.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same special-value semantics as dec32_mul followed by dec32_add.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let np_ab be dec32_propagate_nan(a, b)
    If np_ab is not equal to 0:
        Return np_ab
    End If
    Let np_c be dec32_propagate_nan(c, c)
    If np_c is not equal to 0:
        Return np_c
    End If
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let kb be __load(b, 8)
    Let kc be __load(c, 8)
    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let sb be __load(b, 0)
    Let sc be __load(c, 0)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let cb be __load(b, 16)
    Let cc be __load(c, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let eb be __load(b, 24)
    Let ec be __load(c, 24)

    Let sign_p be 0
    If sa is not equal to sb:
        Set sign_p to 1
    End If

    Let a_inf be 0
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Set a_inf to 1
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set a_inf to 1
    End If
    Let b_inf be 0
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Set b_inf to 1
    End If
    If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set b_inf to 1
    End If
    Let c_inf be 0
    Let c_sign_for_inf be sc
    If kc is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Set c_inf to 1
    End If
    If kc is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Set c_inf to 1
    End If

    Note: a*b Inf paths
    Let prod_is_inf be 0
    If a_inf is equal to 1:
        If kb is equal to DEC32_KIND_FINITE:
            If cb is equal to 0:
                Return dec32_make_qnan()
            End If
        End If
        Set prod_is_inf to 1
    End If
    If b_inf is equal to 1:
        If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_FINITE:
            If ca is equal to 0:
                Return dec32_make_qnan()
            End If
        End If
        Set prod_is_inf to 1
    End If

    If prod_is_inf is equal to 1:
        If c_inf is equal to 1:
            If c_sign_for_inf is not equal to sign_p:
                Return dec32_make_qnan()
            End If
        End If
        Return dec32_make_infinity(sign_p)
    End If
    If c_inf is equal to 1:
        Return dec32_make_infinity(c_sign_for_inf)
    End If

    Note: All finite. Compute exact product.
    Let coeff_p be ca multiplied by cb
    Let exp_p be ea plus eb

    Note: Now align product with c. Smaller exponent is the alignment exponent.
    Let exp_common be exp_p
    If ec is less than exp_p:
        Set exp_common to ec
    End If

    Let scaled_p be coeff_p
    Let scaled_c be cc
    Let shift_p be exp_p minus exp_common
    Let shift_c be ec minus exp_common

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than shift_p:
        If i is greater than or equal to 16:
            Set i to shift_p
        Otherwise:
            Set scaled_p to scaled_p multiplied by 10
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than shift_c:
        If j is greater than or equal to 16:
            Set j to shift_c
        Otherwise:
            Set scaled_c to scaled_c multiplied by 10
            Set j to j plus 1
        End If
    End While

    Let result_coeff be 0
    Let result_sign be 0
    If sign_p is equal to sc:
        Set result_coeff to scaled_p plus scaled_c
        Set result_sign to sign_p
    Otherwise:
        If scaled_p is greater than scaled_c:
            Set result_coeff to scaled_p minus scaled_c
            Set result_sign to sign_p
        End If
        If scaled_c is greater than scaled_p:
            Set result_coeff to scaled_c minus scaled_p
            Set result_sign to sc
        End If
        If scaled_p is equal to scaled_c:
            Set result_coeff to 0
            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_NEG:
                Set result_sign to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set result_sign to 0
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return dec32_round_coefficient(result_sign, result_coeff, exp_common, rounding_mode)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Square root (IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.2)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_sqrt" takes a as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decimal square root via integer Newton-Raphson iteration on a
    pre-scaled coefficient. Decimal sqrt is non-trivial because the
    exponent must be even after scaling so that the result exponent is
    integral. We scale the coefficient by 10^(2k) where k is chosen so
    that:
        - the exponent (ea + 2k) is even AND
        - the scaled coefficient has at least 2*DEC32_PRECISION digits
          (so the integer sqrt has at least DEC32_PRECISION digits).

    The integer Newton iteration on a 14-digit value converges in ~5
    iterations from a power-of-2 initial guess; we cap at 32 iterations
    for safety even though convergence is monotonic.

    Special cases per IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.4.2:
        sqrt(qNaN) = qNaN
        sqrt(-0) = -0
        sqrt(+Inf) = +Inf
        sqrt(x < 0) = qNaN (invalid operation)
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NaN propagation.
    2. Negative-nonzero check -> qNaN.
    3. Zero -> zero with halved exponent (rounded toward even).
    4. Inf -> Inf.
    5. Scale ca up by 10^(2k) where k = ceil((2*PRECISION - digits(ca))/2)
       plus an extra pair if needed to make ea+2k even.
    6. Integer Newton iteration:
          x = (initial guess)
          repeat:
            new_x = (x + scaled / x) / 2
            if new_x >= x: break
            x = new_x
       The classical Newton method converges quadratically; the
       "monotonic decrease" stopping criterion is the standard integer
       sqrt termination per Knuth TAOCP Vol 2 Section 4.3.1 Exercise 16.
    7. Halve the exponent and round to precision.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Iteration count is bounded by ~30 for a 14-digit input which is
    sub-microsecond on any modern CPU. The initial guess is computed
    by isolating the high bit (log2 estimate) so we start within a
    factor of 2 of the true root.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Negative input signals invalid operation per IEEE 754-2008 Section
    7.2 and returns qNaN. -0 returns -0 (not qNaN) per Section 5.4.2.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_QNAN:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)

    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Return dec32_make_infinity(0)
    End If

    If ca is equal to 0:
        Note: sqrt(-0) = -0 per Section 5.4.2
        Return dec32_unpacked_create(sa, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, 0, ea divided by 2)
    End If

    If sa is equal to 1:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Note: Scale up to ensure we have enough digits after the sqrt for
    Note: PRECISION digits of result, AND ensure the exponent is even.
    Let scaled be ca
    Let exp_work be ea
    Let target_digits be DEC32_PRECISION multiplied by 2

    While dec32_count_digits(scaled) is less than target_digits:
        Set scaled to scaled multiplied by 100
        Set exp_work to exp_work minus 2
    End While
    Note: Ensure exp_work is even.
    If exp_work minus ((exp_work divided by 2) multiplied by 2) is not equal to 0:
        Set scaled to scaled multiplied by 10
        Set exp_work to exp_work minus 1
    End If

    Note: Initial guess: 10^(digits/2)
    Let initial_digits be dec32_count_digits(scaled)
    Let guess_digits be (initial_digits plus 1) divided by 2
    Let guess be dec32_pow10(guess_digits)
    If guess is equal to 0:
        Set guess to 1
    End If

    Note: Integer Newton iteration with monotonic-decrease termination.
    Let iter be 0
    Let done be 0
    While done is equal to 0:
        If iter is greater than 64:
            Set done to 1
        Otherwise:
            If guess is equal to 0:
                Set guess to 1
            End If
            Let new_guess be (guess plus (scaled divided by guess)) divided by 2
            If new_guess is greater than or equal to guess:
                Set done to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set guess to new_guess
                Set iter to iter plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: At this point guess = floor(sqrt(scaled)). Determine round bits
    Note: by examining guess^2 vs scaled and (guess+1)^2 vs scaled.
    Let guess_sq be guess multiplied by guess
    Let next_guess be guess plus 1
    Let next_sq be next_guess multiplied by next_guess
    Let result_coeff be guess

    Note: Standard round-half-even on the integer sqrt. The exact
    Note: midpoint test compares 4*scaled against (2*guess+1)^2.
    Let mid_sq be (next_guess multiplied by 2) minus 1
    Set mid_sq to mid_sq multiplied by mid_sq
    Let four_scaled be scaled multiplied by 4
    If four_scaled is greater than mid_sq:
        Set result_coeff to next_guess
    Otherwise:
        If four_scaled is equal to mid_sq:
            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_HALF_EVEN:
                Let last be result_coeff minus ((result_coeff divided by 2) multiplied by 2)
                If last is not equal to 0:
                    Set result_coeff to next_guess
                End If
            End If
            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_HALF_UP:
                Set result_coeff to next_guess
            End If
            If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_POS:
                Set result_coeff to next_guess
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Exponent of sqrt result is exp_work/2.
    Let result_exp be exp_work divided by 2

    Return dec32_round_coefficient(0, result_coeff, result_exp, rounding_mode)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Conversions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_from_integer" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Exact conversion from a 64-bit Integer to Decimal32. If |value|
    exceeds DEC32_MAX_COEFF the result must be rounded to DEC32_PRECISION
    digits; we delegate to dec32_round_coefficient with
    rounding_mode = HALF_EVEN.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. If value is 0, return positive zero.
    2. Else split sign from magnitude.
    3. Call dec32_round_coefficient with exp=0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) for values that fit in 7 digits (the dominant case); O(log10
    value) for the rounding path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope

    If value is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_zero(0)
    End If
    Let sign be 0
    Let mag be value
    If mag is less than 0:
        Set sign to 1
        Set mag to 0 minus mag
    End If
    Return dec32_round_coefficient(sign, mag, 0, DEC32_ROUND_HALF_EVEN)
End Process

Process called "dec32_to_integer" takes a as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convert Decimal32 to a 64-bit Integer, rounding per rounding_mode.
    Inf and NaN cannot be represented as Integer; we return 0 as a
    sentinel and the caller is expected to check is_finite first.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NaN / Inf -> 0.
    2. Adjust coefficient by exponent: if exp >= 0, multiply by 10^exp;
       if exp < 0, divide by 10^(-exp) with rounding.
    3. Apply sign.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(|exp|).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Overflow to 0 sentinel rather than wrap-around.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    If ka is not equal to DEC32_KIND_FINITE:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let result be ca
    If ea is greater than 0:
        Let factor be dec32_pow10(ea)
        If factor is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set result to result multiplied by factor
    End If
    If ea is less than 0:
        Let neg_e be 0 minus ea
        Let divisor be dec32_pow10(neg_e)
        If divisor is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let quotient be result divided by divisor
        Let remainder be result minus (quotient multiplied by divisor)
        Let half be divisor divided by 2
        Let round_up be 0
        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_HALF_EVEN:
            If remainder is greater than half:
                Set round_up to 1
            Otherwise:
                If remainder is equal to half:
                    Let last_digit be quotient minus ((quotient divided by 2) multiplied by 2)
                    If last_digit is not equal to 0:
                        Set round_up to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_HALF_UP:
            If remainder is greater than or equal to half:
                If remainder is not equal to 0:
                    Set round_up to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_POS:
            If sa is equal to 0:
                If remainder is greater than 0:
                    Set round_up to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If rounding_mode is equal to DEC32_ROUND_TOWARD_NEG:
            If sa is equal to 1:
                If remainder is greater than 0:
                    Set round_up to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set result to quotient
        If round_up is equal to 1:
            Set result to result plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If sa is equal to 1:
        Return 0 minus result
    End If
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String I/O - canonical round-trip surface for decimal values
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_from_string" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses a Decimal32 from a null-terminated ASCII string. Accepted
    grammar (subset of IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.12.2 + RFC-style):
        sign? digits ('.' digits)? (['e' | 'E'] sign? digits)?
        sign? 'Inf' | 'Infinity'
        sign? 'NaN' | 'sNaN'

    This is the CANONICAL conversion to Decimal: the user types a
    decimal literal, the parser converts it to a Decimal32 with
    exactly the typed value, with no binary-to-decimal rounding loss
    en route. This is the property that makes 0.1 + 0.2 = 0.3 work
    correctly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Skip leading whitespace.
    2. Parse optional sign.
    3. Match infinity / NaN keywords.
    4. Otherwise accumulate digits into coefficient, counting fractional
       digits as exponent reductions.
    5. Parse optional exponent and combine with the fractional count.
    6. Round to precision.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(length). Single-pass, no allocation until the final unpacked
    triple is built.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must pass a valid null-terminated buffer. Out-of-range
    exponents are clamped via dec32_round_coefficient's overflow /
    underflow path.
    @End Security_Scope

    If s is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Let pos be 0
    Note: Skip leading whitespace (space, tab, LF, CR).
    Let scanning_ws be 1
    While scanning_ws is equal to 1:
        Let bws be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
        If bws is equal to 32:
            Set pos to pos plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If bws is equal to 9:
                Set pos to pos plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If bws is equal to 10:
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    If bws is equal to 13:
                        Set pos to pos plus 1
                    Otherwise:
                        Set scanning_ws to 0
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let sign be 0
    Let bsign be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
    If bsign is equal to 45:
        Set sign to 1
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End If
    If bsign is equal to 43:
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End If

    Note: Detect Infinity (case-insensitive prefix "inf").
    Let bi1 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
    Let bi2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos plus 1)
    Let bi3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos plus 2)
    Let is_inf be 0
    If bi1 is equal to 73:
        If bi2 is equal to 110:
            If bi3 is equal to 102:
                Set is_inf to 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If bi1 is equal to 105:
        If bi2 is equal to 110:
            If bi3 is equal to 102:
                Set is_inf to 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If is_inf is equal to 1:
        Return dec32_make_infinity(sign)
    End If

    Note: Detect NaN.
    Let bn1 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
    Let bn2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos plus 1)
    Let bn3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos plus 2)
    Let is_qnan be 0
    If bn1 is equal to 78:
        If bn2 is equal to 97:
            If bn3 is equal to 78:
                Set is_qnan to 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If bn1 is equal to 110:
        If bn2 is equal to 97:
            If bn3 is equal to 110:
                Set is_qnan to 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If is_qnan is equal to 1:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Let coeff be 0
    Let frac_digits be 0
    Let saw_digit be 0
    Let saw_dot be 0
    Let scanning_digits be 1
    While scanning_digits is equal to 1:
        Let bd be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
        If bd is equal to 46:
            If saw_dot is equal to 1:
                Set scanning_digits to 0
            Otherwise:
                Set saw_dot to 1
                Set pos to pos plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If bd is greater than or equal to 48:
                If bd is less than or equal to 57:
                    Let digit_value be bd minus 48
                    Set coeff to (coeff multiplied by 10) plus digit_value
                    If saw_dot is equal to 1:
                        Set frac_digits to frac_digits plus 1
                    End If
                    Set saw_digit to 1
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Set scanning_digits to 0
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set scanning_digits to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    If saw_digit is equal to 0:
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Note: Optional exponent.
    Let exp_val be 0
    Let bexp be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
    If bexp is equal to 101:
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    Otherwise:
        If bexp is equal to 69:
            Set pos to pos plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If bexp is equal to 101:
        Note: Already consumed.
        Let exp_sign be 0
        Let bs2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
        If bs2 is equal to 45:
            Set exp_sign to 1
            Set pos to pos plus 1
        End If
        If bs2 is equal to 43:
            Set pos to pos plus 1
        End If
        Let scanning_exp be 1
        While scanning_exp is equal to 1:
            Let be2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
            If be2 is greater than or equal to 48:
                If be2 is less than or equal to 57:
                    Set exp_val to (exp_val multiplied by 10) plus (be2 minus 48)
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Set scanning_exp to 0
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set scanning_exp to 0
            End If
        End While
        If exp_sign is equal to 1:
            Set exp_val to 0 minus exp_val
        End If
    End If
    If bexp is equal to 69:
        Let exp_sign2 be 0
        Let bs3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
        If bs3 is equal to 45:
            Set exp_sign2 to 1
            Set pos to pos plus 1
        End If
        If bs3 is equal to 43:
            Set pos to pos plus 1
        End If
        Let scanning_exp2 be 1
        While scanning_exp2 is equal to 1:
            Let be3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
            If be3 is greater than or equal to 48:
                If be3 is less than or equal to 57:
                    Set exp_val to (exp_val multiplied by 10) plus (be3 minus 48)
                    Set pos to pos plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Set scanning_exp2 to 0
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set scanning_exp2 to 0
            End If
        End While
        If exp_sign2 is equal to 1:
            Set exp_val to 0 minus exp_val
        End If
    End If

    Let final_exp be exp_val minus frac_digits
    Return dec32_round_coefficient(sign, coeff, final_exp, DEC32_ROUND_HALF_EVEN)
End Process

Process called "dec32_to_string" takes a as Integer, buffer as Integer, buffer_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a canonical text form of a Decimal32 into the caller's buffer
    per IEEE 754-2008 Section 5.12.2. The text uses the natural
    coefficient + 'E' + exponent form unless the value can be
    expressed in plain digits without an exponent in <= buffer_size
    characters. Returns the byte length written (excluding terminator),
    or 0 on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Handle NaN ("NaN" + terminator).
    2. Handle Infinity ("Inf" or "-Inf").
    3. For finite values, write sign (if negative), then coefficient
       digits, then 'E' and exponent.
    4. Always null-terminate at the end.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(digits). At most DEC32_PRECISION (7) coefficient digits and
    ceil(log10(EMAX-EMIN+1)) = 3 exponent digits.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller controls buffer_size. If insufficient (less than 16 bytes for
    worst case "-9999999E-101\0") we write nothing and return 0.
    @End Security_Scope

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If buffer_size is less than 16:
        Return 0
    End If
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let pos be 0
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_QNAN:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 0, 78)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 1, 97)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 2, 78)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 3, 0)
        Return 3
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 0, 115)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 1, 78)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 2, 97)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 3, 78)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 4, 0)
        Return 4
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 0, 73)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 1, 110)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 2, 102)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 3, 0)
        Return 3
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 0, 45)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 1, 73)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 2, 110)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 3, 102)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, 4, 0)
        Return 4
    End If

    Let sa be __load(a, 0)
    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    If sa is equal to 1:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, pos, 45)
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End If

    Note: Emit coefficient digits (at least one digit even for zero).
    If ca is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, pos, 48)
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Note: Build digits by collecting them right-to-left, then writing
        Note: them left-to-right.
        Let digits_buf be 0
        Let buf_pos be 0
        Let c_work be ca
        Let temp_buffer be Layout.allocate(32)
        If temp_buffer is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        While c_work is greater than 0:
            Let d be c_work minus ((c_work divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
            Memory.memory_set_byte(temp_buffer, buf_pos, d plus 48)
            Set buf_pos to buf_pos plus 1
            Set c_work to c_work divided by 10
        End While
        Let k be buf_pos minus 1
        While k is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let d2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(temp_buffer, k)
            Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, pos, d2)
            Set pos to pos plus 1
            Set k to k minus 1
        End While
        Layout.deallocate(temp_buffer)
    End If

    Note: Always emit exponent in 'E<int>' form for unambiguous round-trip.
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, pos, 69)
    Set pos to pos plus 1
    Let e_work be ea
    If e_work is less than 0:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, pos, 45)
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        Set e_work to 0 minus e_work
    End If
    If e_work is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, pos, 48)
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Let e_buf be Layout.allocate(16)
        If e_buf is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let e_pos be 0
        While e_work is greater than 0:
            Let ed be e_work minus ((e_work divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
            Memory.memory_set_byte(e_buf, e_pos, ed plus 48)
            Set e_pos to e_pos plus 1
            Set e_work to e_work divided by 10
        End While
        Let m be e_pos minus 1
        While m is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let ed2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(e_buf, m)
            Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, pos, ed2)
            Set pos to pos plus 1
            Set m to m minus 1
        End While
        Layout.deallocate(e_buf)
    End If

    Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, pos, 0)
    Return pos
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Encoding / decoding to the 32-bit BID interchange form
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dec32_encode_bid" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes an unpacked triple into the 32-bit BID interchange form per
    IEEE 754-2008 Section 3.5.2. BID stores the entire coefficient as a
    plain binary integer in the trailing significand field, with the
    sign in bit 31 and the biased exponent in bits 30..23 (for the
    short BID form) or split across the combination field for the
    extended form.

    For Decimal32 the BID-32 layout is:
        bit 31:        sign s
        bits 30..23:   biased exponent (8 bits)  - upper combination
        bits 22..0:    coefficient continuation (23 bits = up to 8388607)

    Numbers whose coefficient does not fit in 23 bits use the alternate
    encoding (bits 30..29 = 11) with a longer exponent field. We
    implement BOTH forms.

    Result fits in the low 32 bits of an Integer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. NaN/Inf: bits 30..27 = 11111 (Inf) or 11110 (NaN)? Per IEEE
       754-2008 Section 3.5.2 Table 3.5: the combination bits are
           11110 -> +/- Infinity
           111110 -> qNaN
           111111 -> sNaN
       We emit:
           sign | 0x78000000 for +Inf
           sign | 0x7C000000 for qNaN
           sign | 0x7E000000 for sNaN
    2. Finite: compute biased_exp = exponent + DEC32_BIAS. Clamp to
       [0, DEC32_MAX_BIASED_EXP].
       If coefficient < 2^23 (8388608): use small-coefficient form:
           bits 31:    sign
           bits 30..23: biased_exp[7..0]
           bits 22..0:  coefficient
       Else: use large-coefficient form:
           bits 31:    sign
           bits 30..29: 11
           bits 28..21: biased_exp[7..0]
           bits 20..0:  coefficient & 0x1FFFFF | (coefficient_high << 21)
       In Decimal32 the coefficient is at most 9999999 < 2^24 so the
       large-coefficient form encodes the top bit implicitly via the
       11 prefix.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Bitwise composition, no allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Out-of-range exponents are clamped via the upstream
    dec32_round_coefficient; this routine assumes a normalized triple.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 2143289344
    End If
    Let ka be __load(a, 8)
    Let sa be __load(a, 0)

    Let sign_bit be 0
    If sa is equal to 1:
        Set sign_bit to 2147483648
    End If

    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_POS_INF:
        Return sign_bit bitwise or 2013265920
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_NEG_INF:
        Return sign_bit bitwise or 2013265920
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_QNAN:
        Return sign_bit bitwise or 2080374784
    End If
    If ka is equal to DEC32_KIND_SNAN:
        Return sign_bit bitwise or 2113929216
    End If

    Let ca be __load(a, 16)
    Let ea be __load(a, 24)
    Let biased be ea plus DEC32_BIAS
    If biased is less than 0:
        Set biased to 0
    End If
    If biased is greater than DEC32_MAX_BIASED_EXP:
        Set biased to DEC32_MAX_BIASED_EXP
    End If

    Note: Small-coefficient form: coefficient fits in 23 bits.
    If ca is less than 8388608:
        Let encoded be sign_bit bitwise or (biased shifted left by 23)
        Set encoded to encoded bitwise or ca
        Return encoded
    End If

    Note: Large-coefficient form: prefix 11, then 8 exponent bits, then
    Note: 21 coefficient bits with the high 3 implied via the prefix.
    Let prefix be 1610612736
    Let encoded2 be sign_bit bitwise or prefix
    Set encoded2 to encoded2 bitwise or (biased shifted left by 21)
    Let masked be ca bitwise and 2097151
    Set encoded2 to encoded2 bitwise or masked
    Return encoded2
End Process

Process called "dec32_decode_bid" takes bits as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decodes a 32-bit BID into an unpacked triple. Inverse of
    dec32_encode_bid.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Extract sign from bit 31.
    2. Inspect bits 30..23:
         11110xxxx -> Inf, bit 27 distinguishes signaling from quiet NaN.
         11111xxxx -> NaN.
         11_xxxxxx -> large-coefficient form.
         other     -> small-coefficient form.
    3. Build unpacked triple via dec32_unpacked_create.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Bitwise extraction, single allocation for the resulting triple.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure. Garbage input still produces a well-formed triple (possibly
    NaN or Inf).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sign_bit be bits bitwise and 2147483648
    Let sign be 0
    If sign_bit is not equal to 0:
        Set sign to 1
    End If

    Let combo be (bits shifted right by 26) bitwise and 31

    If combo is equal to 30:
        Return dec32_make_infinity(sign)
    End If
    If combo is equal to 31:
        Let nan_bit be (bits shifted right by 25) bitwise and 1
        If nan_bit is equal to 1:
            Return dec32_make_snan()
        End If
        Return dec32_make_qnan()
    End If

    Let biased be 0
    Let coeff be 0
    Let high_two be (bits shifted right by 29) bitwise and 3

    If high_two is equal to 3:
        Note: Large-coefficient form
        Set biased to (bits shifted right by 21) bitwise and 255
        Set coeff to bits bitwise and 2097151
        Set coeff to coeff bitwise or 8388608
    Otherwise:
        Set biased to (bits shifted right by 23) bitwise and 255
        Set coeff to bits bitwise and 8388607
    End If

    Let exp_val be biased minus DEC32_BIAS
    Return dec32_unpacked_create(sign, DEC32_KIND_FINITE, coeff, exp_val)
End Process
